### 1. How Pi Extensions Register Tools (`registerTool` API)

Pi extensions register tools via `pi.registerTool(definition)`. The definition object has this shape:

```typescript
pi.registerTool({
  name: "tool_name",                    // Unique identifier the LLM calls
  label: "Tool Label",                  // Display name in TUI
  description: "What the tool does",    // Shown to the LLM
  promptSnippet: "One-liner in system prompt Available tools section",  // Optional
  promptGuidelines: ["Use my_tool when..."],  // Optional, appended to Guidelines section
  parameters: Type.Object({...}),       // Typebox schema for arguments
  prepareArguments(args) { ... },       // Optional legacy compat shim (pre-validation)
  async execute(toolCallId, params, signal, onUpdate, ctx) {
    // signal — AbortSignal, check signal?.aborted
    // onUpdate — stream progress: onUpdate({ content: [...], details: {...} })
    // ctx — ExtensionContext (cwd, sessionManager, model, etc.)
    return {
      content: [{ type: "text", text: "result for LLM" }],
      details: { /* structured data for rendering */ },
      terminate: true,  // Optional: skip follow-up LLM call
    };
  },
  // Optional custom TUI rendering:
  renderCall(args, theme, context) { ... },
  renderResult(result, options, theme, context) { ... },
});
```

Key rules:
- Use `StringEnum` from `@earendil-works/pi-ai` (not `Type.Union`/`Type.Literal`) for string enums — Google API compatibility
- **Throw errors** to signal failure (sets `isError: true`); returning a value never sets the error flag
- Tools **must truncate output** (default 50KB / 2000 lines) using `truncateHead`/`truncateTail` from `@earendil-works/pi-coding-agent`
- Can register via `defineTool()` helper for cleaner separation:
  ```typescript
  import { defineTool } from "@earendil-works/pi-coding-agent";
  const tool = defineTool({ name: "...", parameters: ..., execute: ... });
  export default function (pi: ExtensionAPI) { pi.registerTool(tool); }
  ```
- Tools are callable immediately after `registerTool()` — no reload needed

---

### 2. CloakBrowser JavaScript API for Browsing

CloakBrowser is a drop-in Playwright/Puppeteer replacement. The JS API:

**Launch browser:**
```javascript
import { launch, launchContext, launchPersistentContext } from 'cloakbrowser';

// Basic (headless, stealth binary auto-selected)
const browser = await launch();

// With options
const browser = await launch({
  headless: false,
  proxy: 'http://user:pass@proxy:8080',
  geoip: true,
  humanize: true,
  args: ['--fingerprint-noise=false'],
});

// Browser + context in one call
const context = await launchContext({
  userAgent: 'Custom UA',
  viewport: { width: 1920, height: 1080 },
  locale: 'en-US',
  timezone: 'America/New_York',
});

// Persistent profile (cookies survive restarts)
const ctx = await launchPersistentContext({
  userDataDir: './chrome-profile',
  headless: false,
  proxy: 'http://user:pass@proxy:8080',
});
```

**Navigate and get content (standard Playwright API):**
```javascript
const page = await browser.newPage();
await page.goto('https://example.com', { waitUntil: 'domcontentloaded' });

// Get page content
const html = await page.content();       // Full page HTML
const title = await page.title();        // Page title
const url = page.url();                  // Current URL

// Extract text
const text = await page.locator('body').innerText();
const innerHtml = await page.locator('.main').innerHTML();

// Evaluate JS
const result = await page.evaluate(() => document.querySelector('h1')?.textContent);

// Wait for elements
await page.waitForSelector('.content', { timeout: 10000 });
const visible = await page.locator('.content').isVisible();

// Screenshot
await page.screenshot({ path: 'page.png', fullPage: true });

// Interact
await page.locator('input#search').fill('query');
await page.locator('button[type=submit]').click();

// Close
await browser.close();
```

**Key CloakBrowser-specific options:**
| Option | Purpose |
|--------|---------|
| `humanize: true` | Bezier mouse curves, per-char typing, realistic scroll |
| `geoip: true` | Auto-detect timezone/locale from proxy IP |
| `proxy: 'http://...'` | HTTP or SOCKS5 proxy |
| `args: [...]` | Chromium flags (`--fingerprint=noise=false`, etc.) |

---

### 3. Minimal Extension File Structure

**Single file (simplest):**
```
~/.pi/agent/extensions/
└── cloak-browser.ts
```

**Directory with dependencies (recommended for npm packages):**
```
~/.pi/agent/extensions/
└── cloak-browser/
    ├── package.json
    ├── package-lock.json
    ├── node_modules/        # After npm install
    └── src/
        └── index.ts
```

```json
// package.json
{
  "name": "cloak-browser",
  "dependencies": {
    "cloakbrowser": "^0.3.31",
    "playwright-core": "^1.50.0"
  },
  "pi": {
    "extensions": ["./src/index.ts"]
  }
}
```

**Minimal `index.ts` skeleton:**
```typescript
import type { ExtensionAPI } from "@earendil-works/pi-coding-agent";
import { Type } from "typebox";
import { truncateHead, DEFAULT_MAX_BYTES, DEFAULT_MAX_LINES, formatSize } from "@earendil-works/pi-coding-agent";

export default function (pi: ExtensionAPI) {
  pi.registerTool({
    name: "cloak_browse",
    label: "CloakBrowse",
    description: "Browse a URL with stealth browser, return page content",
    promptSnippet: "Browse a website using a stealth browser to bypass bot detection",
    promptGuidelines: [
      "Use cloak_browse when the user needs to access a website that blocks automated requests, or when standard web requests fail."
    ],
    parameters: Type.Object({
      url: Type.String({ description: "URL to browse" }),
      waitUntil: Type.Optional(Type.String({ description: "Playwright waitUntil: 'domcontentloaded' | 'networkidle'" })),
    }),
    async execute(_toolCallId, params, signal, _onUpdate, ctx) {
      const { launch } = await import("cloakbrowser");
      const browser = await launch({ headless: true });
      try {
        const page = await browser.newPage();
        await page.goto(params.url, {
          waitUntil: (params.waitUntil as any) ?? "domcontentloaded",
          signal,
        });
        const title = await page.title();
        const html = await page.content();
        const truncation = truncateHead(html, {
          maxLines: DEFAULT_MAX_LINES,
          maxBytes: DEFAULT_MAX_BYTES,
        });
        return {
          content: [{ type: "text", text: `Title: ${title}\n\n${truncation.content}` }],
          details: { url: params.url, truncated: truncation.truncated },
        };
      } finally {
        await browser.close();
      }
    },
  });
}
```

**Placement options (from docs):**

| Location | Scope |
|----------|-------|
| `~/.pi/agent/extensions/*.ts` | Global (all projects) |
| `~/.pi/agent/extensions/*/index.ts` | Global (subdirectory) |
| `.pi/extensions/*.ts` | Project-local |
| `.pi/extensions/*/index.ts` | Project-local (subdirectory) |

**Test quickly:**
```bash
pi -e ./cloak-browser.ts
```

Or add to `settings.json`:
```json
{ "extensions": ["~/.pi/agent/extensions/cloak-browser"] }
```

---

## Evidence
- Pi extensions docs: `/Users/shivam94/.hermes/node/lib/node_modules/@earendil-works/pi-coding-agent/docs/extensions.md` — `registerTool` API, tool definition shape, output truncation requirements, file structure patterns
- CloakBrowser README: `https://raw.githubusercontent.com/CloakHQ/CloakBrowser/main/README.md` — JS API for `launch()`, `launchContext()`, `launchPersistentContext()`, Playwright page API
- Example extensions: `examples/extensions/hello.ts` (minimal tool), `examples/extensions/truncated-tool.ts` (truncation + rendering pattern)

## Caveats
- CloakBrowser auto-downloads a ~200MB Chromium binary on first use — the `execute()` function will be slow on first call
- The dynamic `import("cloakbrowser")` inside `execute()` is a workaround for extensions that may not have `node_modules/` at declaration time; if you use the package.json structure with npm install, a top-level import works fine
- CloakBrowser uses Playwright under the hood — `page.click()` on ElementHandles bypasses humanization. Use selector-based methods (`page.locator().click()`) for human-like behavior
- Headless mode may still be detected on some aggressive sites (DataDome, Kasada) — document this in `promptGuidelines`
- No browser session persistence across tool calls by default — each `cloak_browse` call launches and closes a fresh browser. For persistent browsing, you'd need to manage a browser instance in extension state via `pi.on("session_start")` / `pi.on("session_shutdown")` lifecycle hooks
- Extensions run with full system permissions — only load trusted extensions

